1177":"circa 1177","about 1175":"circa 1175","1207":"1207","Closeburn, Dumfriesshire, Scotland":"Closeburn, Dumfriesshire, Schotland","Carrick, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Carrick, Ayrshire, Schotland","Scotland":"Schotland","of Scotland":"Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"Abt 1146–Abt 1207":"about 1146–about 1207","1146–1207":"1146–1207","–Female":"Deceased","1148–Female":"1148–Deceased","1175–1250":"1175–1250","1177–1232":"1177–1232","1128–1150":"1128–1150","1153–1179":"1153–1179","about 1150":"about 1150","1153":"1153","1175":"1175","1250":"1250","1150":"1150","Abt 1207":"about 1207","1128":"1128","1148":"1148","Abt 1146":"about 1146","1179":"1179","1146":"1146","1232":"1232","1177":"1177","about 1148":"about 1148","about 1177":"about 1177","about 1175":"about 1175","1207":"1207","Closeburn, Dumfriesshire, Scotland":"Closeburn, Dumfriesshire, Scotland","Carrick, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Carrick, Ayrshire, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland","of Scotland":"Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Kirkpatrick","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from either of two places in Dumfriess called Kirkpatrick or any of various other places in Scotland, all so named from the dedication of their church to Saint Patrick. The Scottish word <i>kirk</i> sometimes replaced Gaelic <i>cill</i> ‘church’ in placenames; compare   Kilpatrick  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Kilpatrick","meanings":["Irish (Ulster): shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Giolla Phádraig</b> ‘son of the servant of (Saint) Patrick’ (Irish <i>Pádraig</i>). See also   Fitzpatrick  .","Scottish: habitational name from any of various places called in Gaelic as <i>cill Padraig</i> ‘church of (Saint) Patrick’. See also   Kirkpatrick  ."]}]},{"name":"of","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Young, Sung, Jung, Yong, Chang, Kwang, Sang, Dong, Hyun, Jae, Jin, Kyung, Jong, Chong, Chung, Byung, Jeong, Pyong, Myong, Hak, Jin Hwan, Sook, Yeong, Choon.","Korean: variant of   O  .","Japanese: variant of <b>Ō</b> (see   O  )."],"variants":[{"name":"O","meanings":["(1997: 122;2010: NA)","Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Young, Bo Young, Chae, Chong Hwan, Dong Kun, Ho, Hwan, Hyun, Jong, Jung, Ki Soon, Kwang.  Korean Min, Chong, Chol, Jung Ho, Myong, Sa, Sung Kyun.","Korean (오; Chinese character: 吳): historically, there were two Chinese characters for the O surname, but by the late Koryŏ period (14th century  AD ), one of them had disappeared. Some records indicate that there are as many as 210 different clans for the remaining character, but only sixteen can be positively documented. All sixteen of these clans originate from the same ancestor, O Ch’ŏm (吳 瞻), who migrated to Korea from China during the reign of Shilla's King Chijŭng (500–514  AD ). <i>O</i> is a common surname throughout Korea. Compare   Oh  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Lord William Kirkpatrick of Closeburn was born about 1146, in Closeburn, Dumfriesshire, Scotland, United Kingdom, his father, Ivon Kirkpatrick of Closeburn, was 20 and his mother, Euphemi